	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				The mentioning of RAM is a big issue with EQ. Where most people think that getting DSL or LAN connetions to speed up EQ will find out that is not helping as much as they thought. Actually, more of you are having problems with EQ and your DSL connections. <BR>
<BR>
To play EQ to its fullest, make sure your have openGL supported graphic card with DirectX 7.0a(I have noticed there is no difference in graphic card frame rate if you choose a 2meg card or a 16meg card (RIVA TNT compared to Diamond Stealth 3D)). Your resolution (how good the game looks)will depend on your cards features. EQ isn't really taxing video wise as compared to some games even though the graphics are exceptional. <BR>
<BR>
Processor speed is an issue but with my pentium 1 233mhz processor i can run it fine. I would suggest at least P2 or faster.<BR>
<BR>
RAM is EQ's work horse. Its legendary &quot;loading&quot; message can be cut down by adding more RAM. At the moment I am running 64 meg PC66 RAM. Yeah, imagine it. <BR>
<BR>
Overall, if you want a good gaming system your going to need a good team. Your Video, Processor, and Memory all work together in overall speed of EQ. As for the bad news... for some reason, no matter how fast your modem is... lag is always a &quot;beast&quot;.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
